Honestly, this movie is more of a fairy tale to me, wherein the case is open to public at the time, people are allowed to participate in some kind of march to express their disapproval, the victim himself gets to live to talk about it later when time allows, and most importantly, there's enough information left to let history judge. The reality is, in most countries on planet earth, this kind of story happens so often, people just gets numb about it: No one is able to reveal the truth, the ones that get remotely close get vaporized. It won't appear on newspaper and there will not be a single word about it in any historical document. I'm really surprised by the fact that people here in the U.S are allowed to talk about some very touchy topics(without worried about safely), and I think they should be grateful for this privilege.
